<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1912-07-07T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1912-07-07T00:00:00-05:00" n="225" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d225">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 893.51/986.</note>
                            <head>
                                <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">British Chargé
                                        d’Affaires</gloss> to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                        State</gloss></hi>.</head>
                            <opener>
                                <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.—Paraphrase.]</seg>
                            </opener>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right">
                                    <placeName>
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">British Embassy</hi>, <lb/>
                                        <hi rend="italic">Kineo, Me.</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1912-07-07">
                                        <hi rend="italic">July 7, 1912</hi></date>.</dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>The French Minister at Peking has been instructed that the French
                                Government consider the best means of obtaining consent of China to
                                proposed conditions is to suspend any advance. The British Minister
                                has been similarly instructed.</p>
                            <closer>
                                <signed>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Mitchell Innes.</hi>
                                </signed>
                            </closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>